#	Peer review 

## Introduction

*This part of the homework will focus on the article authored by Niki Marjerrison et al. 2022, Comparison of cancer incidence and mortality in the Norwegian Fire departments  cohort, 1960-2018* Occupational & Environmental Medicine *79(11) :736-742. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/35589382/. Read the full article before answering the questions.*

## Guiding questions

### What study population is being investigated?

The study investigates male employees of Norwegian fire departments:

4,295 men from 15 fire departments across Norway

Follow-up period: 1960–2018 (58 years)
 
### What are the main data sources used in this study?**

The study used three main registry data sources:

Cancer Registry of Norway (CRN) — provided cancer diagnosis dates and sites (mandatory reporting since 1952, high completeness)

Cause of Death Registry — provided underlying cause and date of death, based on death certificates

National Population Register — provided emigration dates

### What reference (standard) population is used for calculating the standardized ratios?**

The general Norwegian male population was used as the reference, with national rates applied to calculate both SIRs and SMRs.

### What standardization method is used? How can you tell?

The study uses indirect standardization. 

This can be inferred because the authors calculated SIRs and SMRs, which are the product of indirect standardization, dividing the observed number of cases or deaths in the cohort by the expected number derived from applying reference population rates to the cohort's own age and period distribution.

### Is this method appropriate in this study? Justify (2-4 sentences)

Yes, indirect standardization is appropriate here. The cohort is relatively small, meaning many cancer sites have few observed cases, which makes direct standardization unstable. Indirect standardization is preferred in occupational cohort studies precisely because it handles small numbers more reliably by borrowing the age-period structure from the larger reference population.

